full_text:
I tend to agree regarding the definitions of beliefs. There seems to be a continuum: at each end are people with closed minds who operate from a dogma of philosophy and beliefs. In each case their positions are relatively unshakable. One end is the staunch believer and the other end is what I and others have come to call the &#39;pseudoskeptic&#39;. It is this latter type of person who often labels themselves a &#39;skeptic&#39; and who tries to argue from what they term positions of &#39;logic&#39;, say they are &#39;critical thinkers&#39; and demand &#39;evidence&#39; placing their faith in their version of &#39;science&#39;. All of these terms are of their own definition and are maleable depending on the situation. In the center of this spectrum are what I think of as the true and only &#39;open-minded critical thinkers&#39;. I suppose one could label these individuals as &#39;skeptics&#39; but this kind of clouds the issue. I am sad to say that I really believe the size of this third group is well under 1/3 of everyone. Just my opinion of course.



--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, Zack Widup &lt;w9sz.zack@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; In my mind the word &quot;skeptic&quot; is a misnomer. There is a difference between a
&gt; skeptic and an unbeliever.
&gt; 
&gt; If I said &quot;I&#39;m skeptical about your rebuilding that engine&quot; I would admit
&gt; that it&#39;s possible, just doubt that you&#39;re going to do it.  An unbeliever
&gt; wouldn&#39;t believe that it&#39;s even possible to rebuild engines.
&gt; 
&gt; I think most of the &quot;skeptics&quot; we see in any sort of paranormal sphere are
&gt; really unbelievers. As Frank pointed out, they don&#39;t even believe or
&gt; recognize that we ARE spirits, so how could a ghost exist and how could the
&gt; box work? A ghost could hit them in the head with a 2X4 and they still
&gt; wouldn&#39;t believe it.
&gt; 
&gt; Zack
